synco: Differences between synonymous codon-specific Ramachandran plots

Code description

This code reproduces the analyses presented in [2], showing that differences between the codon-specific Ramachandran plots provided in [[3]] are not statistically significant. The two-sample goodness-of-fit tests that have been used for the analyses were introduced in [1], whose implementation is available in the R package torustest.

  • The file codon_test.R performs the goodness-of-fit test assessing the null hypothesis Amino-acid backbone distribution does not depend on the identity of the translated codon. Codon-specific Ramachandran plots are defined for a given amino-acid without taking into account nearest neighbors effects. The analysis is carried out on the experimental dataset provided in [3] and on the same structures extracted from the AlphaFold database. Instructions to perform the analyses are provided in the file, that produces Figures 2a, 2b and results described in Section D of the SI in [2].

  • The same null hypothesis, but taking neighboring residues into account, is tested in codon_test_tripeptides.R. Here, the codon-specific Ramachandran plots contain conformations coming from a fixed tripeptide (fragment of three consecutive amino-acids). This analysis uses the function get_tripeptides, which uses the sequence information of the dataset provided in [3] to extract neighbors identities. The code reproduces the analysis presented in Section E of the SI in [2].

  • The simulation study described in Section B of the SI in [2] is reproduced in simulation_study.R. This files produces also Figure 1 in [2].

For any inquires, please file an issue or contact us.

Results of the supplementary analyses

Here, we present the figures depicting results of the analyses presented in Sections C (Figure S1), D and E (Figure S2) of the SI in [2].



Related work

Check Akeju & Cope paper for a complementary analysis of the codon and bond angles correlation described in Rosenberg et al. 2022.

[3] Rosenberg, A.A., Marx, A. & Bronstein, A.M. (2022). Codon-specific Ramachandran plots show amino acid backbone conformation depends on identity of the translated codon. Nat Commun, 13, 2815. https://doi.org/10.1038/s41467-022-30390-9.

[4] Akeju, O.J., Cope, A. L. (2024). Re-examining Correlations Between Synonymous Codon Usage and Protein Bond Angles in Escherichia coli. Genome Biology and Evolution, 16(5): evae080. https://doi.org/10.1093/gbe/evae080.
